---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About | Automation, Over Time"
  description="What this project documents and why it exists"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl py-8">
    <h1 class="mb-8 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight text-zinc-900 dark:text-zinc-100">About</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none dark:prose-invert">
      <p>
        This blog exists to document how a test automation effort evolved over time, not as a
        greenfield initiative, but inside a long-lived environment with existing systems,
        constraints, and expectations.
      </p>

      <p>
        The application under test was a large, centralized enterprise platform responsible for core
        operational records and workflows. It followed a regular upgrade cycle, and each upgrade
        required careful confirmation that critical paths continued to behave as expected.
      </p>

      <p>
        Those confirmations took the form of predictable smoke and sanity checks. They were
        intentionally conservative by design, focused on validating that unchanged behavior remained
        unchanged after each upgrade.
      </p>

      <p>
        Because those checks were required every cycle and shared across multiple functional areas,
        they became the natural starting point for automation. Making them executable reduced
        repetition and produced results that other groups relying on the same platform could trust.
      </p>

      <p>
        As that foundation stabilized, the effort gradually widened. Teams using the platform for
        different operational needs could rely on the same signals, rather than maintaining parallel
        manual checks. From there, groups supporting connected systems began asking whether the same
        approach could help manage their own upgrade paths and integrations.
      </p>

      <p>
        That expansion was not planned up front. It happened because once the work became
        repeatable, it was difficult to justify continuing to do similar work by hand elsewhere.
        This blog captures that entire process: the early assumptions, the missteps, the moments where
        structure became necessary, and the decisions to introduce new capability only after
        stability was established.
      </p>

      <p>
        All details are intentionally abstracted. Nothing here documents internal systems or speaks
        on behalf of any institution. The perspective is mine, shaped by the constraints I worked
        within, and focuses on the patterns and trade-offs of the journey.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you’re interested in my background or other work, that lives elsewhere. You can find it
        at
        <a href="https://alvindcastro.github.io/"> alvindcastro.github.io</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
